The library isn’t dead ya’ll!!! You can still check out books for free like you did when you were a kid, but digitally if you like.

All you need is a library card AND the Libby app. 
You connect your library card in the app, and BOOM, you can check out digital books. 
You get 3 weeks before they need to be returned (you can extend the rental if no one is waiting for the book)

Sure, the more popular books often have a wait list, but just put the books you are hoping to read on hold, and when it’s your turn you will get notified.

4 things I am currently focusing on…

1. SLEEP: sleep is the number one focus each day for us. We will not sacrifice our sleep at this stage of our life (note: have a sacrificed my sleep in the past…yes. I understand that everyone has different stages of their life where sleep is harder. Just sharing my number one focus)

2. HAIR HEALTH: I started coloring my hair when I was 20. Since then it has been just about every cut and color imaginable. I am in a phase of life where I am no longer coloring it, or cutting it (beyond a trim to remove split ends), letting it dry and be styled naturally more often, and wearing it down more than up. It’s my hairs time to shine…literally!

3. QUIET/STILLNESS: I have been go-go-go for as long as I can remember. Sitting still or being in stillness was a struggle. I am leaning more into quiet spaces, not always trying to fill them with “things”. Embracing the magic that is the sound of nature and quiet.

4. BEAUTY MY WAY: I love that so many people love make-up. I am happy that it makes them happy. But, I have always felt the most “beautiful” when I am bare faced. I spent a good portion of my life trying to fit into the box of the beauty industry by wearing bright pink lipstick or applying fake lashes (if you love this, awesome. Not saying it’s wrong, telling you what’s right for me). I am working on not only being bare faced at home, but at events, in photos, for all of life…basically wearing makeup only if I want to, not because I feel like it would be weird not to.

What are some things you are currently focused on and why?! Would love to hear!

Bye bye digital, hello analog!

I have been full e-reader for well over a year now. BUT, I was starting to use it less and less. I didn’t want to pick it up and read, which is odd for me because I LOVE to read. 

We will make a change in an instant — based on new information, a gut instinct, a feeling, an energy shift. And that’s what I did. I decided to ditch the Kindle and go back to physical books. I wanted to scan the shelves at a bookstore. I wanted to feel the weight of it in my hand. I want to pass it off to someone else when I am done.

The kindle served me well for the time I was using it. I am grateful for the time we had together, and am even more grateful to be able to go back to one of the oldest past times of all…turning the pages of a good book. 

Don’t be afraid to make a change. Listen to your instincts, and let your energy and inner voice guide you towards what feels best for you!

Happy Reading!

🎵I wear my sunglasses at night…so I can, so I can….

SLEEP!

Darren and I have been wearing blue light blocking glasses for as long as I can remember. We have daytime ones for when we are on our computers, and we have these “sunset” ones for the time after sunset until it’s time to sleep. 

Artificial blue light tricks our bodies into thinking it’s still daytime, which messes with our circadian rhythm. You want natural blue light during the day, which is why it’s important to spend some time outside. But artificial blue light can be damaging to your eyes and disturbing to our sleep. 

Technology is incredible. And trust me I love watching a good show at night like anyone else. But I also love doing what I can to reset my body to “factory settings” . I don’t want to be blue light toxic. And it’s easy to be that in today’s modern world.

1.  Just start moving 
You may not want to work out, but once you get started, a few minutes in, you feel amazing and your whole energy has shifted and changed. Same is true for life. Take action. Not sure what to do? Do one thing. Take one small step. After you take that first step, the next step will be a little bit easier. 

2. You are stronger than you think you are 
There is always that moment in a workout, where you decide to up the weights, and you are surprised by how strong you have gotten. You can’t believe that you now can do 3 pushups on your toes, where before you could barely do one on your knees. You’ve got this. Whatever THIS is. You have strength you didn’t even know you had. Don’t be afraid to “lift heavy!”

3. Results don’t happen overnight
You can’t do one workout and expect to have reached all your fitness goals. No differently than you can’t just try one thing in business or in life and expect for all your dreams to come true. It’s consistent effort, day in and day out, that lead to change. It’s the compound effect of showing up, putting in the work, doing the things, and over time seeing those small wins and celebrating them. 

4. Take a break when you need it
When I teach group fitness, I always tell my class, “take a break when you need it”. You don’t have to wait for the instructor to tell you it’s okay, and you don’t have to wait for the interval to be over. If you need a moment to collect yourself and take a breath, DO IT! You will come back stronger. That’s life. Sometimes we just need a damn minute. And after we take that pause, take some clarifying breaths, we can come back with a renewed sense of purpose and passion. 

5. Don’t forget to stretch
The warm-up and the cooldown are two of the most valuable parts of a workout, yet, they are often the part that people skip over the most. Think of your morning routine as your warm-up and your nighttime routine as your cooldown. The way you start and end your day are KEY to your success and overall well-being. Skip a warm-up or a cooldown, and you might pull a muscle. Don’t have a dialed in morning or night routine, and you might miss out living an extraordinary day.
